I know this is not a genealogical question, but if if it's ok to ask/get answer:

1. What is the Azores Portuguese word for &quot;Sweetheart&quot;
2. Is Mosca the word and correct spelling for &quot;fly&quot;.  My grandmother used to go after flys w/swatter in hand, saying what sounded like &quot;Mooshka Diaube&quot; (devil fly).  Is mosca pronounced mooushe-ka?
</POST>
<POST>
<POSTER> Marra...@cs.com </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-02T17:09:00 </POSTDATE>
In a message dated 11/2/2007 5:04:10 PM Eastern Daylight Time,

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
avm6 ... @bak.rr.com writes:
&gt; 1. What is the Azores Portuguese word for &quot;Sweetheart&quot;
&gt;  2. Is Mosca the word and correct spelling for &quot;fly.&quot;  My grandmother used
&gt; to go after flys w/swatter in hand, saying what sounded like &quot;Mooshka Diaube&quot;
&gt; (devil fly).  Is mosca pronounced mooushe-ka?
">

1- Querido (a); 2-Namorado (a) (actually your girlfriend or boyfriend,
fiancé, etc.)
2- Yes to the spelling and yes to the pronunciation. Your grandmother
probably mumbled something like &quot;Corisca mosca do diabo!&quot; as she chased them with the
swatter. At least that is what my grandmother did.

John
</POST>
<POST>
<POSTER> &quot;Arlene Marcoux&quot; &lt;avm6...@bak.rr.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-02T17:11:00 </POSTDATE>
I don't think there is a word for &quot;Sweetheart&quot;.   There is Querido for darling, dear beloved or bem-amado (masculine) bem-amada (feminine) for well beloved or loved one.  It's probably how they phrase it.
Fly is spelled Môsca.  With the accent it is probably pronounced with the Mooshka sound.  That is the way I heard it.

Arlene M.

