grew up with it and it was not considered derogatory. It was only a  name
for their people which was easier to say. I also have worked extensively in
Hawaii and have heard the term all the time, toward me and others. In
Hawaii, the Portuguese people who immigrated there worked in the cane fields
right along with the Kamaheinas and were considered ³one of them². Thus ther
term Hopa Haule was used. A white man going to the islands is considered a
Houle, a white man. A hopa is a half white and is accepted as one of them in
the islands. I have used the term lots of times when I was working and they
thought I was a houle. I would just inform them I¹m not houle, I¹m hopa.
