Gotta Love Wikipedia,
**
*Portagee* is a term often ascribed to persons of
Portuguese&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portuguese_people &gt;ancestry.
The term found usage during the major waves of Portuguese
immigration to the United States&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States &gt;,
from the late 1870s until the recent wave, which began in the 1960s.

Initially, the term found usage by Anglo-Saxons of the
WASP&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_Anglo-Saxon_Protestant &gt;variety
in describing the immigrants from Southern
Europe &lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southern_Europe &gt; that they encountered
as fisherman and factory workers in New
England&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_England &gt;and on farms in
California &lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California &gt;. Although ethnically
white Caucasians, at the time, the Portuguese faced the same discrimination
and accusations of
non-Caucasian&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caucasian_race &gt;heritage
that befell
Irish &lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_people &gt;,
Italians&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_people &gt;and
Jews &lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jews &gt; of that era.

While the term still carries a derogatory connotation in some parts of the
country, in other areas of the United States, persons of Portuguese descent
often call each other *Portagee* as a term of bonding and endearment. This
seems more common in New England, where Portuguese from the
Azores&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azores &gt;and
Madeira &lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madeira &gt; Islands have settled since
the late nineteenth century. More recent immigrants to New
Jersey&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Jersey &gt;do not use the term as
much.

In California, a *portagee gate* characterized the tightwad stereotype
attributed to Portuguese immigrants. The gate involved flimsy construction,
implying that the Portuguese who made it attempted to save money in
purchasing materials. A 2004 biography by Charles Reis
Felix&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Reis_Felix &gt;,
entitled *Through A Portagee
Gate&lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Through_A_Portagee_Gate&amp;act...; &gt;
*, makes reference to the usage of *portagee* as an ethnic term in
Massachusetts during the 20th century. Felix analyzes the term while
examining his own Portuguese-American roots and those of his father.

The term *portagee* also denotes a type of beans typically eaten by the
Portuguese, as well as a type of bread eaten with meals. The term supposedly
originated from a mispronunciation of the word *Portuguese* itself.
Residents of Hawaii &lt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaii &gt; are also familiar
with the term, which was also applied in a derogatory fashion to Portuguese
workers from Madeira who harvested sugar cane on the islands.
-M2

