I'm from Fall River, MA and let me tell you, when I was a kid, if someone called me or my friends a Portagee it was a fighting word.  It was definitely considered a slur especially if it came with a few adjectives before it.  As everyone should know, Cape Verdean's especially those in the New Bedford area, were colored in skin, considered themselves and rightfully so as Portuguese.  They were not afro/americans but Portuguese.  The caucasian portuguese in Fall River were at times called &quot;Black Portagee's&quot; by the Irish and French kids in the city.  Needless to say we had a lot of problems with that.  A common slur became a racist slur.  We went through it all. A common saying was &quot;What kind of geese don't fly&quot;?  and  the answer was &quot;portagees&quot;.  They even had tee shirts with this saying and depicted Daffy Duck flying.  It just made us more determined to succeed, and we did.  I think that there were a couple of movies about fisherman, one with Spencer Tracy, one with Gilbert Roland and Moby Dick that used the word &quot;Portagee&quot; to describe one of the sailors.  In the correct context it was o.k.  I guess in the correct context everything is acceptable.

Ron

