Here on the coast of San Mateo county at least, we call the part of a
fence that is a wire gate or wire gap a Portagee gate. It might have
three of four barb wires going across, like the fence it it part of,
plus a couple of pickets to space the wires and keep them from tangling
when you draw it aside to open it. The wires are attached permanently
at one end to a post and then to a picket at the other end that is
joined top and bottom to with wire loops to a post that is set in the
ground.

And people of Azorean descent are Portagees. Or maybe were--I am
speaking of the older generation. I don't know how the newer immigrants
feel about the word.

But to old timers, that wire gap is still a Portagee gate.

When I was in the Azores I saw only one and took a picture of it. I
don't think the idea came from there because most of their fences are
rock walls!

Mary Bordi

