Remember one thing. When my mother was growing up there, it was the late
1930¹s to early 1940¹s. She watched the bombing of Pearl. My Grandfather was
able to get the family on the first ship to leave Honolulu Harbor after it
was cleared. That was about May 1942. Now, when I was working over there,
that was in the late 70¹s to mid 1980¹s. That was when I had my personal
experience with the term. About two years ago, this came up on another web
site that I belong to and was ³hotly debated². Everyone voiced their
opinion. I have been in Hawaii and have first hand knowledge of what I said.
I have even called as early as two years ago, my friend who was in charge of
Honolulu Fire Dept Arson Detail. I asked him the question, as to whether the
term is still used and is it an insult or just a term. He confirmed what I
already knew, it¹s just a term for someone Portuguese. Normally, however, it
is not used for Œmainlanders¹ as then it would be an insult. It is used
between friends. As he told me, he is Korean, and he will call his good
friends Portagee, but only his friends. They, in turn, have nick names they
called him. So, I don¹t know what to say about this. I have heard that on
