Portuguese in Hawaii

Before Hawaii became a state there were two kinds of schools.  One for  those
who spoke pidgen-English or poor Englilsh...the other school, the English
Standard  was for those who spoke good English.  It was almost like a  private
school.  I attended one of the few English Standard schools in  Honolulu.
These schools were primarly for the Haoles (white person or  Caucasian).  Chinese,
Japanese, Portuguese were tested by the principal -  tested to see that they
spoke good English.  I do not remember being  tested...but others remembered
the terrible ordeal.

In the years I attended this school there were very few Portuguese.  I  mean
a few.  There were more Japanese and Chinese than there were  Portuguese.  I
used to hear comments from older Portuguese family members  complain that the
Portuguese in Hawaii were a disgrace...it seemed they never  wanted to better
themselves - quitting school early, getting a job and getting  married - while
the orientals bettered themselves with education.  So many  doctors and
lawyers were Orientals...so few were Portuguese.

I have stock in 4 Hawaii companies.  Once a year I receive the Annual
Report...lots of pictures - pictures of the leading people in these  companies.
Most are Haoles (Caucasians) and orientals.  One seldom  sees a Portuguese name.

Now if the following is not discrimination I don't know what discrimination
is:   If you move to Hawaii and you are Greek, Italian, Turkish and  Spanish
(not hispanic) you are a Haole (Caucasian).  But if a Portuguese  moves to
Hawaii he is never a Haole.  One can read - yes, in a  newspaper,  &quot; Caucasians
were represented along with Japanese, Chinese and  Portuguese...&quot;

On my visits to Hawaii ( I do not have the Hawaiian accent- I can spot it a
mile away) if I meet some local people and I mention I am Portuguese, the
reply,  is, Oh, I thought you were a Haole.

I know that my cousins there would not stand for anyone calling them
Portagee.  They don't even like jokes about it. They think many  Portuguese in
Hawaii do not show respect for their racial background.  I know of others who keep
their mouths shut when called a Portagee...they  don;'t like it but rather
than make a fuss they keep quiet.

Toni

