I don¹t know what years you were in High School, but my mother has told me
many times how she, her sister and elder brother went to the ³Portuguese
school McKinley High . They would not go to the ³white or Haole school²
because their younger brother and sister were not allowed there. You see,
when they moved to Hawaii, my Grandmother had married a Korean. That¹s the
reason they moved there to begin with. They were not bothered in Hawaii with
discrimination  since it was a common union of two different races. However,
when my Aunt Peggy and Uncle Billy were young, it was obvious that they were
not ³whites² or haole (thanks for the spelling by the way, I never can
remember the spelling of Haole).
Anyway, she told me to let people know that she went to Mc Kinley High,
instead of Roosevelt High School, which was mainly haole and children of
miltary or the wealthy in Honolulu. My mother told me that they wanted her
to go to Roosevelt but she refused. She was blonde hair blue eyed and very
pretty. She was also the First Princess of the Kamehameha Day parade(similar
to our Rose Parade). She sat on the float just below the Queen. I still have
a picture of her on the float.
So, I will put this the way she just said it on the phone. If a friend
called her Portagee, she really didn¹t get bothered about it. However if a
stranger called her the same thing, then it was insulting. So, it comes down
to this: it¹s not the word itself but who says it to whom that counts.
Hope I have expressed myself alright. Now, I have to go back to bedl
Good night all
Cliff

